viewpoints.name: A1 - Meta-Data Definitions
viewpoints.notes: Architectures, particularly large ones, usually require meta-data tags to aid with searching and discovery.

viewpoints.name: A2 - Architecture Products
viewpoints.notes: The A2 Viewpoint specifies the structure of an architecture, and the products that describe the architecture. Each product may correspond to an architecture view. This viewpoint also traces the architectures onto the Enterprise Phases they correspond to (see also C2 – Enterprise Vision) and identifies the key stakeholders, their concerns and the products that address those concerns (from ISO/IEC/IEEE Standards).

viewpoints.name: A3 - Architecture Correspondence
viewpoints.notes: ISO/IEC/IEEE42010 introduces the idea of architecture correspondence and correspondence rules. Quoting from ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010; “A correspondence defines a relation between AD (Architecture Description) elements. Correspondences are used to express architecture relations of interest within an architecture description (or between architecture descriptions). Correspondences can be governed by correspondence rules. Correspondence rules are used to enforce relations within an architecture description (or between architecture descriptions).”

viewpoints.name: A4 - Methodology Used
viewpoints.notes: The A4 Viewpoint specifies the methodology used for the architecting activities. This methodology is described in NAFv4 Chapter 2. The content of the A4 viewpoint can also be modeled in the A1 viewpoint.

viewpoints.name: A5 - Architecture Status
viewpoints.notes: Since NAFv3.0, it has been possible to assign version numbers to views and specify their approval dates. In NAFv4.0, this is integrated with the meta-model’s generic project and milestone approach so that architecture releases are tracked against the architecture delivery project. The content of the A5 viewpoint can also be modeled in the A1 viewpoint.

viewpoints.name: A6 - Architecture Version
viewpoints.notes: Where the A5 Viewpoint shows the current version number and approval status for the architecture, the A6 Viewpoint shows the complete history of the architecture.

viewpoints.name: A7 - Architecture Compliance
viewpoints.notes: The A7 Viewpoint gives the overall specification of architecture meta-data.

viewpoints.name: A8 - Standards
viewpoints.notes: The A8 Viewpoint encompasses both technical and non-technical standards. The standards specified in the A8 view can be applied across the architecture to a variety of structural and behavioural elements. Standards are essential to the coherent running of businesses and to the delivery of reliable, interoperable systems.

viewpoints.name: Ar - Architecture Roadmap
viewpoints.notes: The Ar Viewpoint shows the history of the architecture project as well as its future direction.

ArchitecturalDescription.notes: An Architecture Description is a work product used to express the Architecture of some System Of Interest. It provides executive-level summary information about the architecture description in a consistent form to allow quick reference and comparison between architecture descriptions -- It includes assumptions, constraints, and limitations that may affect high-level decisions relating to an architecture-based work program.

ArchitectureMetadata.notes: Information associated with an ArchitecturalDescription, that supplements the standard set of tags used to summarize the Architecture. It states things like what methodology was used, notation, etc.

ActualProject.notes: A time-limited endeavor to provide a specific set of ActualResource that meet specific Capability needs.

ActualProjectMilestone.notes: An event with a start date in a ActualProject from which progress is measured.

Standard.notes: A ratified and peer-reviewed specification that is used to guide or constrain the architecture. A Standard may be applied to any element in the architecture.

Finding.notes: An ascertainment made in the model, which relates to the methodology used, the subject under consideration, the tool or something else.

Recommendation.notes: Need for action from a finding.

ActualOrganization.notes: An actual formal or informal organizational unit, e.g. "Driving and Vehicle Licensing Agency", "UAF team Alpha".

ActualPost.notes: An actual, specific post, an instance of a Post "type" - e.g., "President of the United States of America." where the Post would be president.

Concern.notes: Interest in an EnterprisePhase (EnterprisePhase is synonym for System in ISO 42010) relevant to one or more of its stakeholders.

Organization.notes: A group of OrganizationalResources (Persons, Posts, Organizations and Responsibilities) associated for a particular purpose.

Person.notes: A type of a human being used to define the characteristics that need to be described for ActualPersons (e.g. properties such as address, telephone number, nationality, etc).

Post.notes: A type of job title or position that a person can fill (e.g. Lawyer, Solution Architect, Machine Operator or Chief Executive Officer).

Project.notes: A type that describes types of time-limited endeavours that are required to meet one or more Capability needs.

View.notes: An architecture view expresses the architecture of the system-of-interest in accordance with an architecture viewpoint (or simply, viewpoint). [ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011(E)].

Viewpoint.notes: An architecture viewpoint frames (to formulate or construct in a particular style or language) one or more concerns. A concern can be framed by more than one viewpoint. [ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011(E)].

Responsibility.notes: The type of duty required of a Person or Organization.

ActualEnterprisePhase.notes: The ActualState that describes the phase of an Enterprise endeavor.

EnterprisePhase.notes: A current or future state of the wholeLifeEnterprise or another EnterprisePhase.

WholeLifeEnterprise.notes: A WholeLifeEnterprise is a purposeful endeavor of any size involving people, organizations and supporting systems. It is made up of TemporalParts and StructuralParts.

Information.notes: A comment that describes the state of an item of interest in any medium or form -- and is communicated or received.

Protocol.notes: A Standard for communication over a network. Protocols may be composite, represented as a ProtocolStack made up of ProtocolLayers.

ProtocolLayer.notes: Usage of a Protocol in the context of another Protocol. Creates a whole-part relationship.

Protocolstack.notes: A sub type of Protocol that contains the ProtocolLayers, defining a complete stack.

Classified.notes: Relationship that indicates which classification an element has.

DescribedBy.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description describes an architecture.

Expresses.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description includes the following architectures.

ArchitectureForProject.notes: A relationship that expresses that a architectural description belongs to a actual project.

ConformsTo.notes: A relationship that expresses that an UAFElement conforms to a standard.

RealizesRecommendation.notes: Relation states that a Recommendation is realized through this element.

RefersTo.notes: Relationship that assigns a finding to a recommendation.

ResultsFrom.notes: Relationship expresses that an element of architecture is the reason for a finding.

StakeholderConcern.notes: A relationship that expresses which concern a stakeholder has.

CompliesViewpoint.notes: Relationship that expresses that a view has been created according to the specifications of a viewpoint.

ConcernForView.notes: A relationship that expresses which concerns are covered by view.

ConcernForViewpoint.notes: A relationship that expresses which concerns are covered by viewpoint.

ViewpointsInArchitecturalDescription.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description includes the following viewpoints.

ViewpointToStakeholder.notes: A relationship that expresses which stakeholder needs viewpoint.

ViewsInArchitecturalDescription.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description includes the following views.

ArchitecturalReference.notes: A tuple that specifies that one architectural description refers to another.

ArchitecturalSequence.notes: A relationship that specifies that one architectural description is the successor of another.

SameAs.notes: A tuple that asserts that two elements refer to the same real-world thing.

RatifiedStandards.notes: A relationship that expresses that an actual organization releases a standard.
